canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of abdominal bloating, early satiety, and increasing abdominal girth. She has lost 5 kg in weight over this period. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reached menopause at age 51 years. Her older sister was diagnosed with breast cancer at age 45 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. A fixed mass is palpable in the left lower quadrant. Pelvic examination reveals a firm, irregular adnexal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT abdomen/pelvis shows a complex left ovarian mass with peritoneal deposits and moderate ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate tumour marker to request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-fetoprotein","CA-125","CA 15-3","CA 19-9","Carcinoembryonic antigen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features highly suspicious for advanced ovarian cancer. The choice of appropriate tumour marker is crucial for initial assessment and subsequent monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA-125\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate tumour marker for epithelial ovarian cancer. It is elevated in approximately 80% of epithelial ovarian cancers and is particularly useful in post-menopausal women where there are fewer benign causes of elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for germ cell tumours and hepatocellular carcinoma. While it can be elevated in some ovarian germ cell tumours, these are rare in post-menopausal women and typically present differently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA 15-3\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as a tumour marker for breast cancer. While this patient has a family history of breast cancer, her presentation is not suggestive of breast malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA 19-9\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used in pancreatic cancer and biliary tract malignancies. While it can be elevated in some ovarian cancers, it is not the most appropriate first-line tumour marker for this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used in colorectal cancer monitoring. While it may be elevated in some ovarian cancers, it is less sensitive and specific than CA-125 for ovarian malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile no tumour marker is perfect, CA-125 remains the most appropriate choice in this clinical scenario. It can be used both for initial assessment and, if elevated, for monitoring response to treatment and surveillance for recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["CA-125 is the most appropriate tumour marker for epithelial ovarian cancer, being elevated in 80% of cases.","CEA is primarily used for colorectal cancer monitoring and has limited utility in ovarian cancer.","Tumour markers should be interpreted in conjunction with clinical findings and imaging as no single marker is diagnostic."],"references":["Practitioners TRAC of general. Australian Family Physician. The Royal Australian College of general Practitioners; [cited 2024 Dec 11]. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54821"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17201"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54821"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T20:52:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T20:53:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9891"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69368"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitab